com.ibm.xmi.framework
Class Workspace

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--com.ibm.xmi.framework.Workspace
public class Workspace
extends java.lang.Object

A workspace is a collection of Models and XMIFiles instances. Its purpose is to enable the framework to match the objects and their values in an XMI file with the corresponding classes and their features when an XMI file is loaded.

If the Model for the data is not known, the framework assumes that the contents of XMI files are objects and Value.DATA values, so other kinds of values will not be created unless you write your own reader adapter.

If you use this class, all the values for the objects in the files will be restored correctly, and you will not need to write a reader adapter to do it.

To use this class, you need to do the following steps (steps 2 and 3 can be done in any order, but must be done before step 4):

  1. Make a workspace
  2. If you have not already done so, add your Model instances to the workspace.
  3. If you have not already done so, add at least one XMIFiles instance to the workspace.
  4. Use the XMIFiles object(s) added to the workspace to load XMI files; the framework will attempt to match the objects and values in XMI files with the classes and features in the models you have added to the workspace, so all the values will be created by the framework as appropriate.

A declaration in the framework object model is either a package, a class, or a feature of a class.

getDeclaration

public Data getDeclaration(ValueInfo info,
                           Data data,
                           boolean ignoreNamespace)
This method is used by the framework to get the definer for the value corresponding to the given info from an XMI file. If the framework knows what kind of value to make, it does so and passes it as the data parameter to ensure that the value returned is of the correct type.

For XMI 1.0, namespaces are ignored.

You will not normally use this method; the framework uses it in the ReaderAdapterImpl.

Parameters:
info - A ValueInfo instance from the framework
data - Either a property or link
ignoreNamespace - True for XMI 1.0; false otherwise.

getDeclaration

public Data getDeclaration(java.lang.String xmiName,
                           Namespace namespace,
                           XMIFile.Model model,
                           java.lang.String className,
                           Data data,
                           boolean ignoreNamespace)
This method returns the class or feature that is the definer for the given data.

First, this method attempts to determine which model the definer is in by looking for a model that contains a namespace that matches the given namespace, if there is one. If no model is found, the framework searches for a model whose name matches the XMIFile.model name or, if it is null, the namespace name. If the framework still cannot find a model, the models are searched in the order they were added.

Then the framework searches for the class with the given class name, to help direct the search.

If data is an XMI object, the framework searches for an XMI class; if data is a value, the frameworks searches for a feature of the same type as the given one.

If the framework finds more than one construct that matches the criteria, this method returns the first one.

Parameters:
xmiName - The XMI name
namespace - The namespace
model - The XMIFile.Model from the header of an XMI file
className - The name of the class; if data
data - The data to match to its definer; either an XMI object, property, or link
ignoreNamespace - If true, namespaces are ignored; otherwise, they are used to search for the proper definer.
Returns:
Null or a class, property, or link matching the given data

getDeclarations

public java.util.Collection getDeclarations(java.lang.String name,
                                            Data data,
                                            Namespace namespace,
                                            boolean ignoreNamespace)
Return a collection of classes and features in the models added to this workspace whose XMI name matches the given name. If an XMI object, or value of an object is the second parameter, only the correct type of data will be put in the collection. For example, if the data is an XMI object, only classes with the given name will be returned; if data is a value, only features with the same type as the type of the given value will be returned.

If there are no classes or features with the given XMI name, an empty collection is returned.

Parameters:
name - The XMI name
data - Either an XMI object or value
namespace - The namespace
ignoreNamespace - If false, and there is no namespace, namespaces in models are ignored.
Returns:
An empty collection or a collection of classes or features whose XMI name matches the given name and whose type is correct for the type of data given.
